<body>
  <h1>Japanese Weather: Rain (雨が降る) Study Guide</h1>

  <p>
    This page teaches you how to say things like
    <strong>“It rains / It’s raining / It rained”</strong> in Japanese using the verb
    <span class="jp">降る（ふる）</span>.
  </p>

  <div class="note">
    <strong>Key idea:</strong> For rain and snow, Japanese literally says
    “<strong>rain falls</strong>” → <span class="jp">雨が降る（あめがふる）</span>.
  </div>

  <h2>1. Basic Pieces</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><span class="jp">雨（あめ）</span> – rain</li>
    <li><span class="jp">降る（ふる）</span> – to fall (for rain, snow, etc.)</li>
    <li><span class="jp">雨が降る（あめがふる）</span> – it rains / it will rain</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="note">
    <strong>Why が and not は?</strong><br />
    Weather verbs usually use <span class="jp">が</span>:
    <span class="jp">雨が降る</span>, <span class="jp">雪が降る</span>.  
    You can use <span class="jp">雨は</span> for contrast, but <span class="jp">雨が</span> is
    the default.
  </div>

  <h2>2. Important Forms of 雨が降る</h2>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Meaning</th>
        <th>Form</th>
        <th>Japanese</th>
        <th>Romaji</th>
        <th>Notes</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>It rains / will rain</td>
        <td>Plain non-past</td>
        <td class="jp">雨が降る。</td>
        <td>ame ga furu.</td>
        <td>Plain / dictionary form</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>It rains / will rain</td>
        <td>Polite non-past</td>
        <td class="jp">雨が降ります。</td>
        <td>ame ga furimasu.</td>
        <td>Polite</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>It is raining (right now)</td>
        <td>Plain progressive</td>
        <td class="jp">雨が降っている。</td>
        <td>ame ga futte iru.</td>
        <td>“Rain is falling” → right now</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>It is raining (right now)</td>
        <td>Polite progressive</td>
        <td class="jp">雨が降っています。</td>
        <td>ame ga futte imasu.</td>
        <td>Polite “it’s raining”</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>It rained</td>
        <td>Plain past</td>
        <td class="jp">雨が降った。</td>
        <td>ame ga futta.</td>
        <td>Plain</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>It rained</td>
        <td>Polite past</td>
        <td class="jp">雨が降りました。</td>
        <td>ame ga furimashita.</td>
        <td>Polite</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>It doesn’t rain / won’t rain</td>
        <td>Plain negative</td>
        <td class="jp">雨が降らない。</td>
        <td>ame ga furanai.</td>
        <td>Plain negative</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>It doesn’t rain / won’t rain</td>
        <td>Polite negative</td>
        <td class="jp">雨が降りません。</td>
        <td>ame ga furimasen.</td>
        <td>Polite negative</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>3. Example Sentences</h2>

  <div class="example">
    <div class="jp">雨が降ると、ねずみと遊べません。</div>
    <div>ame ga furu to, nezumi to asobemasen.</div>
    <div>When it rains, I can’t play with my rats.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="example">
    <div class="jp">今、雨が降っています。</div>
    <div>ima, ame ga futte imasu.</div>
    <div>It’s raining right now.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="example">
    <div class="jp">きのうは、一日中（いちにちじゅう）雨が降りました。</div>
    <div>kinō wa, ichinichijū ame ga furimashita.</div>
    <div>Yesterday, it rained all day.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="example">
    <div class="jp">あしたは雨が降らないといいですね。</div>
    <div>ashita wa ame ga furanai to ii desu ne.</div>
    <div>I hope it doesn’t rain tomorrow.</div>
  </div>

  <h2>4. Bonus: Just “It’s rainy”</h2>

  <p>
    Sometimes Japanese also just says
    <span class="jp">雨です。</span> (ame desu.)  
    Literally “It is rain.” → “It’s rainy.”
  </p>

  <p>
    But for “<strong>It’s raining (right now)</strong>,” the most natural and common is:
  </p>

  <div class="example">
    <div class="jp">雨が降っています。</div>
    <div>ame ga futte imasu.</div>
  </div>

